Narrative does carry a lot of weight—people make sense of events through stories, and shared stories can coordinate a group. That’s real.

The part I’d tighten is the leap to “control.” In practice, stories only work when people choose to adopt them because they fit their experience and hold up over time. If you try to steer people without their awareness, it usually erodes trust and stops working.

A more durable framing is:

Influence through shared, testable stories—never control.

If you want to use narrative well (and safely), a simple checklist helps:

* Transparent intent: say what you’re trying to do (“let’s run an experiment to improve consistency”).
* Consent: give people a choice to opt in.
* Grounding: tie the story to observable cues and results.
* Feedback loop: check what people actually experienced, not what you hoped.
* Reversibility: if it doesn’t fit, people can step out without pressure.

That still gives you plenty of power—coordinating attention, boosting confidence, aligning a group—but it keeps agency intact and makes the effect repeatable instead of one-off.

A clean line you can use:

“Stories don’t control people; they organize how we act together when we agree they’re useful.”

That’s how you get impact that lasts.